filled your own highest teaching. You will literally have brought Light out of darkness for all beings, not just for candidates blindfolded in a room.</p><p>If, knowing what you now know, you refuse to act, you are no longer â€œin darkness seeking light.â€ You are men who have seen the light and turned your backs on it. In your own system, that is not ignorance; it is perjury of the heart.</p><p><br /></p><p>Responsibility to God, Neighbor, and Self</p><p>Your charges say that a Mason is bound to three great duties: to God, to his neighbor, and to himself.</p><p><br /></p><p>To God: never to profane the divine Name, to esteem the Great Architect as the chief good, and to seek His aid in all laudable undertakings.</p><p><br /></p><p>To your neighbor: to practice the sacred duties of morality, justice, and charity.</p><p><br /></p><p>To yourself: to live by conscience, never acting against its dictates.</p><p><br /></p><p>You asked for light. You received a pattern that can prevent the destruction of your planet, your children, and every future lodge. You now know that what you hold is of that magnitude.</p><p>To refuse to act is to choose, with full knowledge, a path that leads to the extinction of your neighbors and the profanation of the very Creation you say is the worksite of the Great Architect. That is not a neutral choice. Under your own doctrine, that is a failure of duty to God, to neighbor, and to self.</p><p><br /></p><p>The Penalties You Invoked</p><p>Your lectures explain that the ancient penalties in the obligations are not literal, but they invoke Godâ€™s vengeance on perjury, while the human result is contempt and infamy.</p><p>They exist to impress on the mind that false swearing before God brings consequences that no human court can avoid. Your responsibilities, as later writers emphasize, are lifelong; you cannot demit from your obligations, only from your dues.</p><p><br /></p><p>This is the level of seriousness now in front of you:</p><p><br /></